(234, 'showy-aster', 'Showy Aster', 'Western Showy Aster', 167, 'conspicua', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 1, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 200, 0, NULL, '2', 'Sow directly outside in the fall or cold moist stratify for two months then plant on the surface of well drained soil in spring. Keep moist while propagating.', '<p>Showy Aster is a perennial flower native to western North America. It can be found in forest openings and understory, one to three feet tall in height. From July to October, attractive violet to blue flowers with yellow centers bloom in flat topped arrangements. Showy aster Spreads by seed or rhizomes can fill in large spaces, attracting birds and various pollinators.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"759\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230707_144914731-759.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"showy aster flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"760\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230725_141854906-760.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"showy aster flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"761\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230725_141900663-761.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"showy aster leaves\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"},{\"id\":\"762\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230727_011633829-762.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"showy aster leaves\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"},{\"id\":\"763\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230727_012129904-763.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"showy aster flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"764\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230908_184909146-764.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"showy aster seeds\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"}]', 2),
(236, 'yellow-rattle', 'Yellow Rattle', '', 169, 'minor', 'Rhinanthus crista-galli', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 1, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 50, 0, NULL, '2', 'Direct sow about 35 seeds per square foot on the surface of a grassy area. Grass should first be cut short and raked to expose the soil. Yellow Rattle will need other plants (especially grass) to partially feed from. Sowing is best done in the fall as they will need a cold period to break dormancy. Seeds will need light to germinate.', '<p>Yellow rattle is a small annual herb, found circumpolar in the north. It grows in meadows, fields, ditches, and moist to dry grassy areas, tolerating a wide range of soil types. Yellow rattle is hemi-parasitic, relying partly on surrounding plants for nutrition. In this way it can be used in meadow restoration by suppressing dominant grasses and sequestering soil nutrition. This creates better conditions for wildflowers to thrive. Flowers bloom from May to September and are pollinated by bumblebees in the Summer. Seeds follow, and \"rattle\" in their dry capsule pods as the name implies. Yellow rattle is an unmistakable plant with it\'s saw-toothed leaves and bilaterally symmetrical yellow flowers, a unique and beneficial addition to wildflower meadows.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"773\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230810_184038399.MP-773.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"yellow rattle flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"774\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230830_182817618-774.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"yellow rattle seed pods\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"775\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230830_182944708-775.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"yellow rattle seed pods\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"}]', 2),
(237, 'pearly-everlasting', 'Pearly Everlasting', 'Western Pearly Everlasting', 170, 'margaritacea', '', '', '', '', 3, 0, 1, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, '', '', '<p>Pearly everlasting is a small perennial wildflower native to Asia and North America; found in sunny to part shade areas of dry, well drained soil. The plant is very cold hardy, tolerant of drought, salt, and poor soil conditions; a low maintenance perennial that can spread easily to fill in spaces. From June to September, corymbs of attractive pearl coloured bracts surround the yellow flower centers, resembling eggs with yoke centers. They attract pollinators like butterflies, bees and other beneficial insects. plants are either pollen bearing male plants, or seed bearing female ones; both differ slightly in colour. The elegant narrow bluish green leaves along with delicate papery white flowers make for perfect dried flower arrangements, one of the popular uses of pearly everlasting.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"776\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230826_174112546-776.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"pearly everlasting flowers\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"777\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230826_174115707-777.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"pearly everlasting flowers\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"778\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230731_182105098-778.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"pearly everlasting flowers\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"779\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230731_182127030-779.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"pearly everlasting flowers\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"780\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230731_182130779-780.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"pearly everlasting flowers\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(238, 'large-leaf-avens', 'Large-leaf Avens', '', 171, 'macrophyllum', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, '', '', '<p>Large-leaf avens is a late spring perennial of the Rose family, closely related and in resemblance to strawberries and cinquefoils. Native to North America and eastern Asia, the plant is especially common in the Pacific North West, from Alaska to California. Habitats include forest edges and openings, moist woods, and wetlands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From June to August it bears Yellow flowers with five spaced out petals, attracting bees and other pollinators. Probably the most unique feature of large-leaf avens is the long bristly styles creating round pin cushion-like seed heads. The leaves have a variety of interesting shapes and sizes on the same plant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many species and cultivars of Geum exist as garden plants and are easily divided or started via seed. Large-leaf avens is Low maintenance provided it\'s given adequate moisture. The plant also has some medicinal use as a Styptic, astringent, and febrifuge. Indigenous peoples used both the roots and leaves of the plant to make medicine for stomach pain or to aid in pregnancy and delivery.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"795\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230826_150510252-795.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Large-leaf Avens flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"796\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230602_200423452.MP-796.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Large-leaf Avens flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"797\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230826_145741949-797.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Large-leaf Avens flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"798\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230602_200517375-798.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Large-leaf Avens\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"799\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230602_200419530-799.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Large-leaf Avens\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"800\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230826_145809498-800.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Large-leaf Avens seeds\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"801\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230826_173410512.MP-801.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Large-leaf Avens seeds\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"}]', 2),
(239, 'awl-fruited-sedge', 'Awl-fruited Sedge', 'Common Fox Sedge, Prickly Sedge, Spongy Sedge, Stalk-grained Sedge, Owlfruit Sedge, Awlfruit Sedge, Swamp Sedge, Sawbeak Sedge', 172, 'stipata', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, '', '', '<p>Awl-fruited sedge is a cool season perennial of Vulpinae type sedge, native to North America and Asia. Sedges are grouped according to common traits due to the large amount of species (over 600 in North America). Awl-fruited Sedge has many common names including prickly sedge, common fox sedge, stalk-grained sedge, amongst other names. The plant thrives in wet habitats such as waters edge, swamps, floodplains, and wet meadows. Its most prominent features include yellowish-green foliage and interesting green to golden brown prickly seed heads. This plant and establishes quickly, and is a good choice for wetland restoration purposes; tolerates full shade to full sun exposure, is deer-resistant, and attracts birds and native insects.</p>', 8, '[{\"id\":\"810\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230821_210344212-810.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Awl-fruited Sedge\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"811\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230821_210441351-811.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Prickly Sedge\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"812\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230829_211519000.MP-812.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Common Fox Sedge\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"813\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230821_210412412-813.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Common Fox Sedge leaves\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(240, 'northern-bedstraw', 'Northern Bedstraw', '', 173, 'boreale', '', '', '', '', 5, 0, 1, 3, 1, 2, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, '', '', '<p>Northern bedstraw is a fragrant perennial wildflower, widespread in northern regions of North America, Europe, and Asia. It can be found in well drained to moist forested or grassy areas, spreading by both seed and underground rhizomes. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Panicle clusters of showy white flowers appear and bloom all summer from June to August. Narrow whorled leaves radiate out in a circle, directly from the stem turning a deep purplish red in the fall. The plant dies back over the Winter, growing back each year. Northern bedstraw is low maintenance and great in part shade wildflower gardens to compliment other colours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bedstraw has a subtle pleasant fragrance and was used historically to stuff pillows and mattresses, as a cushion and sleep aid. It was also used to filter cow\'s milk of impurities while adding nutritional benefits at the same time. The plant is edible and used medicinally as a blood cleansing tonic.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"819\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230614_171951009-819.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Northern bedstraw\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"820\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230614_171931014-820.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Northern bedstraw\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"821\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230614_172108103-821.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Northern bedstraw\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"822\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230707_235837026-822.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Northern bedstraw\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"823\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230614_172141732-823.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Northern bedstraw leaves\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"},{\"id\":\"824\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230527_013611160-824.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Northern bedstraw leaves\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"}]', 2),
(241, 'crawfords-sedge', 'Crawford\'s Sedge', 'Crawford Sedge', 172, 'crawfordii', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 0, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, '', '', '<p>Crawford\'s sedge is a perennial plant of Ovales type sedge, native to North America and common throughout BC. Sedges are grouped according to common traits due to the large amount of species (over 600 in North America). Ovales often form dense clumps with tufted tops (inflorescence of sessile seed spikes, developing late spring to mid summer. These start as a bright green, turning a nice coppery brown colour. Crawford\'s sedge is usually found in wetlands or wet, sandy, disturbed areas.</p>', 8, '[{\"id\":\"825\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230726_200721635.MP-825.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Crawford\'s Sedge\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"826\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230829_211808102.MP-826.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Crawford\'s Sedge\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"827\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230829_211945983-827.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Crawford\'s Sedge\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"828\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230726_200739250-828.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Crawford\'s Sedge\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(242, 'chamisso-arnica', 'Chamisso Arnica', '', 174, 'chamissonis', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, '', '', '<p>Chamisso arnica is a flowering perennial native to western North America, naturalized in parts of Europe. It can be found in forest edges, moist meadows, and rocky areas; spreading by seed and underground rhizomes. The plant somewhat resembles a small sunflower. Blooms appear in early summer, boasting attractive bright yellow disk flowers surrounded by showy ray petals. Flowering occurs through the summer, attracting bees and butterflies. The flower is used in gardens and does well in high ph, calcareous soils under full sun. Arnicas are commonly used medicinally as a topical oil, poultice, or a cream remedy. Used to treat injuries and insect bites on the skins surface. It Can also be used for muscle aches, pain, rheumatic arthritis, muscular inflammation, and to promote blood circulation to injured areas.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"832\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230727_011603293-832.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Chamisso Arnica\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"833\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230727_011616658-833.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Chamisso Arnica\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"834\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230727_011633829-834.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Chamisso Arnica\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(243, 'great-northern-aster', 'Great Northern Aster', 'Western Bog Aster, Modest Aster, Northwestern Sticky Aster, Giant Mountain Aster', 175, 'modestus', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 1, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 250, 0, NULL, '2', 'Cold moist stratify seeds for two months. In spring, sow directly on the soil surface or scratched just below it as they will need light to germinate. Seeds germinate in about two to three weeks.', '<p>Great northern aster or \"modest aster\" is a flowering perennial plant, native to most Canadian provinces and the northern United States. It Spreads by rhizomes to form colonies in forest openings, along riverbanks or swamps, in part shade to full sun conditions. From a single stem, branches protrude out toward the top accompanied by narrow, lance-shaped leaves. Blooms appear in late summer with corymb flower clusters in resemblance to New England aster. Flowers have narrow purple ray petals with yellow to pale disk centers, attractive to butterflies.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"845\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230819_143927323-845.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"great northern aster flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"844\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230819_144021880-844.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"great northern aster flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"846\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230819_143321152.MP-846.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"great northern aster leaves\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"}]', 2),
(244, 'nodding-beggarticks', 'Nodding Beggarticks', 'Nodding Bur-Marigold, Sticktight', 176, 'cernua', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 50, 50, NULL, '2', 'Soak seeds for 24hrs, then cold moist stratify for 2 months.', '<p>Nodding-beggarticks is an annual wildflower in the Aster family native to North America and Eurasia. It can be found on shores, wetlands, and waters edge under full sun to part shade. Leaves are coarsely toothed and lance-shaped, arranged in opposite pairs. Large showy flower heads resembling sunflowers bloom from August to October. They turn downward as they mature, hence the name cernua, meaning \"nodding\". Ducks sometimes eat the seeds and the flowers are especially attractive to native bees!</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"851\",\"name\":\"original-851.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"nodding beggarticks\",\"caption\":\"\\u00a9 Steve Ansell, some rights reserved (CC-BY-NC)\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"852\",\"name\":\"original-852.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"nodding beggarticks\",\"caption\":\"\\u00a9 J Gibbons, some rights reserved (CC-BY-NC-SA)\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"853\",\"name\":\"original-853.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"nodding beggarticks\",\"caption\":\"\\u00a9 Sokolov Yuriy Ivanovich, some rights reserved (CC-BY-NC)\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"854\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230918_220957541-854.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"nodding beggarticks\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"}]', 2),
(245, 'three-leaf-foamflower', 'Three-leaf Foamflower', 'Foamflower, Sugar Scoops, Cut-leaved Foamflower, Simple-leaved Foamflower', 177, 'trifoliata', '', '', 'trifoliata', '', NULL, 0, 1, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, '', '', '<p>Three-leaf foamflower (Tiarella trifoliata var. trifoliata) is one of the three varieties of foamflower, a delicate enchanting woodland perennial, native to western North America at somewhat higher elevations. It can be found in shaded areas of moist forest understory, coniferous forests, and streambanks; spreading by seed or by underground rhizomes, but not vigorously. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>The plant is upright to leaning, with small pinkish to white flowers that dot long stems above the low foliage. Leaves rise mainly from the base on long stalks and are grouped into three leaflets; hairy, shallow lobed, and toothed. Three-leaf foamflower can have a long bloom period, from spring to early fall. They provide nectar for hover flies and native bees, where seeds are eaten by birds. A perfect ground plant for moist shade gardens and richly mulched hideaways under conifers canopies.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"883\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230707_162240476-883.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Three-leaf Foamflower flowers\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"884\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230602_202908425-884.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Three-leaf Foamflower\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"885\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230707_162314740.MP-885.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Three-leaf Foamflower\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"886\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230707_162450383-886.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Three-leaf Foamflower flowers\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(248, 'arrow-leaved-coltsfoot', 'Arrow-Leaved Coltsfoot', '', 178, 'frigidus', '', '', 'sagittatus', '', 3, 0, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Arrow-Leaved Coltsfoot is a spreading native perennial herb, Found in ditches, swampy forests and wet grasslands.good for rain gardens, to help with water uptake, filtration and erosion control.\r\nAlaska, south to Oregon and across North America in colder areas.\r\n\r\nTall flower heads appear very early spring, bearing white flowers sometimes with hints of pink, purple, or yellow. The flower stalks are somewhat isolated in their emerge. These quickly give way to tufts fluffy seeds to disperse by early June.\r\nLeaves are large and arrow shaped, pale white underneath from soft, fine hairs\r\nColtsfoot has a long history of medicinal use. Native peoples used it as an edible or for chest and stomach conditions. Use with caution as the alkaloids can be damaging if used incorrectly.\r\nThere are a number of variations of this plant; var nivalis and var palmatus are found throughout BC and western North America. var. frigidus is found a cross the globe in very cold climates.', '<p>Arrow-Leaved Coltsfoot is a spreading perennial herb, naturally found in ditches, swampy forests, and wet grasslands. Its native range stretches from Alaska, south to Oregon, and across North America in colder areas. Common uses include rain gardens, water filtration, and erosion control.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tall flower heads appear very early spring, bearing white flowers sometimes with hints of pink, purple, or yellow. The flower stalks are somewhat isolated as they emerge. These quickly give way to tufts of fluffy seeds to disperse by early June. Leaves are large and arrow shaped, forming a pale white underside from soft fine hairs. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Coltsfoot has a long history of medicinal use. Native peoples used it as an edible or for chest and stomach conditions. Use with caution as the alkaloids can be damaging if used incorrectly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a number of variations of this plant; var nivalis and var palmatus are generally found throughout BC and western North America whereas var. frigidus is found a cross the globe in very cold climates.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"909\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240603_0232557172-909.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Arrow-Leaved Coltsfoot\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(249, 'western-larch', 'Western Larch', 'Tamarack, Western Tamarack, Hackmatack, Mountain Larch, Montana Larch', 118, 'occidentalis', '', '', '', '', 2, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 25, 150, '25.00', '2', 'Soak seeds up to 24 hours, then cold moist stratify for 30 days. Plant to a depth of about 1/2 and inch', '<p>Western larch is the largest our native North American larches; found in the interior mountain s of the north west. Well adapted to extreme weather (up to zone 1) and poor soil, provided it\'s well drained.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The wood is similar to Douglas fir, making it useful for logging. Vibrant yellow needdles give it an attractive presence against the greens of other conifers in the fall.</p>', 5, '[{\"id\":\"915\",\"name\":\"PXL_20241102_183655085.MP-915.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Western Larch\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"916\",\"name\":\"PXL_20241102_183444434.MP-916.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Western Larch\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"917\",\"name\":\"PXL_20241102_183544340.MP-917.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Western Larch Fall Colour\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"},{\"id\":\"918\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240820_220933694.PORTRAIT.ORIGINAL-918.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Western Larch Cones\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"919\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240820_221142280-919.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Western Larch Cones\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"}]', 2),
(250, 'Canada-mint', 'Canada Mint', 'American Wild Mint, Chinese Mint, Sakhalin Mint, Japanese Mint, East Asian Wild Mint', 179, 'canadensis', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 50, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'In spring, sow on the soil surface then lightly dust with sand or fine media (seeds will need light to germinate). Keep moist the entire time as this plant requires moisture. No stratification required. Germinates in 10 to 20 days.', '<p>Canada mint is a low but upright, spreading perennial herb native to North America and Asia. \r\nFound growing wild along riverbanks, ponds, or in wet areas; it forms mats of dark green, often with tinted purplish stems, leaf veins, or leaf margins.\r\nClusters of small light blueish to purplish flowers appear in late summer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The therapeutic fragrance is unmistakable, Canada mint is unsurprisingly an important essential oil and medicinal herb. Traditionally, wild mint has been used around the world to stimulate circulation, aid in digestion, and help relieve cold and flu symptoms.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"928\",\"name\":\"25571f30-8b1b-4150-96c8-660e648617df-1_all_615-928.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Canada Mint Flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"929\",\"name\":\"25571f30-8b1b-4150-96c8-660e648617df-1_all_179-929.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Canada Mint Flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"930\",\"name\":\"25571f30-8b1b-4150-96c8-660e648617df-1_all_180-930.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Canada Mint\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"},{\"id\":\"931\",\"name\":\"25571f30-8b1b-4150-96c8-660e648617df-1_all_181-931.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Canada Mint\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"}]', 2),
(252, 'heartleaf-arnica', 'Heartleaf Arnica', '', 174, 'cordifolia', '', '', '', '', 5, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 30, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Seeds needs light to germinate and should sprout within a couple of weeks. Use an acidic soil and preferably grow arnica at elevation but can have success otherwise given good soil and part shade conditions.', '<p>Hearleaf arnica is an attractive perennial wildflower in the sunflower family.\r\nIt\'s native to western North America, found on forest edges, slopes, or meadows at elevation or mountainous areas. The plant gets its name from opposite pairs of heart shaped leaves, but can also be found with arrow shaped, or narrower leaves if grown in drier areas. In spring, flowers with broad golden disk florets with matching yellow disk florets appear. Bloom time may extend as far as late summer. Heartleaf arnica is very similar to broadleaf arnica (Arnica latifolia) and hybridizes with it through most of its range.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"951\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230526_232401736-951.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Heartleaf Arnica\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"952\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230602_195135732-952.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Heartleaf Arnica\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"953\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230602_201116424.MP-953.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Heartleaf Arnica\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"954\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230526_232416695-954.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Heartleaf Arnica\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"955\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230602_193337926-955.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Heartleaf Arnica\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(253, 'kneeling-angelica', 'Kneeling Angelica', '', 180, 'genuflexa', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 3, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 40, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Cold moist stratify for at least 3 months. Seeds require light to germinate.', '<p>Kneeling angelica is a herbaceous perennial plant native to western North America and common to BC. Found in bogs, along waterways, and in wet meadows. In late spring to late summer, Enchanted looking umbels of small white to slightly pink flowers appear. These are held by upright by hollow stems, often tinted with purple.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"961\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240807_143302351.MP-961.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Kneeling Angelica Flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"962\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240807_143240528-962.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Kneeling Angelica Flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"963\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240917_224251473.MP-963.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Kneeling Angelica seed heads\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"964\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240806_025628622.MP-964.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Kneeling Angelica seed heads\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"965\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240807_143252733.MP-965.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Kneeling Angelica leaves\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"}]', 2),
(254, 'labrador-tea', 'Labrador Tea', 'bog labrador tea, Hudson\'s Bay tea, muskeg tea, swamp tea, woolly tea, tundra tea, settler’s tea, bog tea, bog rosemary', 181, 'groenlandicum', '', '', '', '', 4, 0, 1, 6, NULL, NULL, 'slow', 0, 0, 30, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Cold moist stratify for 30days then plant in moist peat and expose to full sun or part shade. Stratifying isn\'t necessary but improves germination. Don\'t allow to dry out after planting.', '<p>Labrador tea is a flowering perennial shrub native to all parts of Canada and much of Northern United States. It can be found colonizing the understory of acidic conifer wetlands, swamps, and bogs. It can also sometimes be seen growing on mountain slopes or on waters edge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The leaves have a unique downward curl along the edges with fuzzy orange undersides. They\'re scented of essential oils and traditionally used to make herbal tea (as the name implies) by native American tribes and early settlers. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fragrant and sticky white flowers appear from late spring to early summer. The evergreen leaves and seed heads persist into winter, providing winter interest for the keen eye.</p>', 6, '[{\"id\":\"976\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240701_153602705-976.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Labrador Tea Flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"977\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240619_034242449-977.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Labrador Tea Flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"978\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240701_153627136-978.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Labrador Tea Flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"979\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240630_024925065-979.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Labrador Tea Flowers\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"flowers\"},{\"id\":\"980\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240619_034228436-980.jpg\",\"tag\":\"4\",\"description\":\"Labrador Tea\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"twigs\\/buds\"},{\"id\":\"981\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240528_233254336.MP-981.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Labrador Tea\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"},{\"id\":\"982\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240528_233122223.MP-982.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Labrador Tea\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"983\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240528_233021710.MP-983.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Labrador Tea\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"984\",\"name\":\"PXL_20241123_230001810.PORTRAIT-984.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Labrador Tea\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"985\",\"name\":\"PXL_20241123_225855352.PORTRAIT-985.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Labrador Tea\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"}]', 2),
(255, 'fragrant-bedstraw', 'Fragrant Bedstraw', 'Sweet-Scented Bedstraw, Cudweed', 173, 'triflorum', '', '', '', '', 5, 0, 1, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 10, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Direct sow in the fall or cold moist stratify for 1.5 months. Plant seeds in moist, well drained soil. Slightly acidic is preferred, but the plant is PH adaptable. Germinates within about 10-15 days.', '<p>Fragrant bedstraw is native to northern boreal forest regions around the world, and south to central America. Commonly found on moist forest floors, spreading by underground stolons. It can be Identified by square stems with whorled leaves. Small white flowers of three give way to seeds which are round and fuzzy. \r\nThe dried herb has a fragrant vanilla scent similar to sweet woodruff (Galium odoratum). The plant also resembles rough bedstraw (Galium asprellum) in appearance.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"992\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240816_150325661.PORTRAIT-992.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"fragrant bedstraw seeds\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"993\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240816_150202326-993.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"fragrant bedstraw\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"994\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240706_174259697.MP-994.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"fragrant bedstraw\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"995\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230826_154457320-995.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"fragrant bedstraw\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"}]', 2),
(256, 'comfrey', 'Comfrey', 'True Comfrey, Boneset, Knitbone, Consound, Slippery-root', 182, 'officinale', '', '', '', '', 4, 0, 0, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p>Comfrey is a flowering perennial herb commonly used medicinally since ancient times. All parts of the plant have been used (with moderation and care) in a variety of ways for treating musculoskeletal injuries amongst other ailments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Purple to pink flowers (sometimes yellowish white) appear from May to June, attracting many pollinators. The boastful flower display, clumping nature, and large leaves can make it an attractive ornamental. It draws up minerals deep within the earth and can be used to enrich/improve the soil for other plants, or in compost as a fertilizer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Comfrey grows in rich forest edges, riverbanks and grasslands; around the world from Asia to Europe, naturalized in North America. With a prominent root system, it\'s very easy to grow and reproduce, even in cold climates. Because of its root reproduction abilities, patch growing, isolation, or pot planting may be a good idea.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"997\",\"name\":\"comfrey-997.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"comfrey patch\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"1042\",\"name\":\"PXL_20250617_221756875-1042.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Comfrey\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1043\",\"name\":\"PXL_20250617_221652760-1043.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Comfrey\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1044\",\"name\":\"PXL_20250617_222007275-1044.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Comfrey\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1045\",\"name\":\"PXL_20250617_221832200-1045.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Comfrey\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(257, 'valerian', 'Valerian', 'All-heal, Garden Heliotrope', 183, 'officinalis', '', '', '', '', 4, 0, 0, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Valerian has a long history as a medicinal herb (mainly for it\'s roots) for mental health, women\'s health, and sleeping disorders. It grows in rich loamy soils; a classic upright plant with unbranched stems and arrays of paired leaflets. In the summer, pinkish to white flower clusters appear, pleasant scented to some. These give way to self seed. Valerian is a favorite of cats and can have a similar effect to catnip.', 7, '[{\"id\":\"998\",\"name\":\"PXL_20250428_014502669.MP-998.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Valerian\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"1051\",\"name\":\"PXL_20250618_191244976-1051.jpg\",\"tag\":\"5\",\"description\":\"Valerian\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1052\",\"name\":\"PXL_20250618_191328095-1052.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Valerian\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(259, 'mackenzie-willow', 'Mackenzie Willow', 'MacKenzie\'s willow', 79, 'prolixa', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, 0, 0, 16, NULL, NULL, 'fast', 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Mackenzie willow is a large multi-stemmed shrub to small tree that can be found on waters edge, mountain valleys, and other wet areas of western North America. Its native range extents from Alaska down to California in the United States. Mackenzie willow can be similar in appearance to the pacific willow and others nearby, distinguished by it near water habitat, reddish brown twigs with blistering mature stems, fine red Petioles, with darkish leaves (paler underneath).', 3, '[{\"id\":\"999\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240610_171616165-999.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Mackenzie willow female catkins\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1000\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240610_171632280-1000.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Mackenzie willow leaves\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1001\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240610_172110660-1001.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Mackenzie willow catkins\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1002\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240610_172117763-1002.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Mackenzie willow leaves\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1003\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240610_172138162-1003.jpg\",\"tag\":\"4\",\"description\":\"Mackenzie willow twigs\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(260, 'drummonds-willow', 'Drummond\'s Willow', '', 79, 'drummondiana', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 0, 16, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Drummond\'s willow is a large multi-stemmed shrub to small tree, distinguished by its glabrous or glaucous branches, brittle at the base. Native to western North America, it occurs from the Yukon down to California and New Mexico in the United States. The tree can be found usually in wet areas like swamps and floodplains, open forest and ditches. Drummond\'s willow is used for native plant restoration of riparian sites, widely grazed by Moose, also used by beaver, deer, and elk. A food source for ducks and various birds.', 6, '[{\"id\":\"1004\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240515_223023697.MP-1004.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"drummond\'s willow catkins\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1005\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240515_223033345.MP-1005.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"drummond\'s willow catkins\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1006\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240515_223041646.MP-1006.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"drummond\'s willow stems\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1007\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240506_170341455-1007.jpg\",\"tag\":\"4\",\"description\":\"drummond\'s willow stems\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(263, 'false-mountain-willow', 'False Mountain Willow', '', 79, 'pseudomonticola', '', '', '', '', NULL, 0, 3, 12, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'False Mountain Willow is a shrub to small tree, native and widespread across North America. Male or female catkins emerge in spring before the leaves, which are often wavy with red stalks. Noted for its large stipules at the base of the stalks.', 3, '[{\"id\":\"1008\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240531_005947884.MP-1008.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"False Mountain Willow Fruit\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"1009\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240521_181807018.MP-1009.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"False Mountain Willow Fruit\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"1010\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240625_183401678-1010.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"False Mountain Willow leaves\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"},{\"id\":\"1011\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240602_034412128-1011.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"False Mountain Willow leaves\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"},{\"id\":\"1012\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240602_034340958-1012.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"False Mountain Willow leaves\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"},{\"id\":\"1013\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240625_183411425-1013.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"False Mountain Willow seeds\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"}]', 2),
(264, 'cow-parsnip', 'Cow Parsnip', 'Pushki, American Cow-parsnip, Indian Rhubarb, Indian Celery, Satan celery, Poison Turnip', 184, 'maximum', '', '', '', '', 5, 0, 0, 10, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p>Cow parsnip is a large herbaceous plant of the carrot family, widely distributed throughout moist areas of North America. It\'s Known for its large dissected leaves and hairy hollow stems, which are sometimes mistaken for Devils Club in appearance.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Flat topped umbels of white flowers bloom late summer to fall, attracting birds and butterflies (a larval host of the Anise Swallowtail). These give way to a large brown display of seed heads. The plant is a good food source for many wild and cultivated animals. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Peeled or cooked stems were widely used by Indigenous North Americans like celery. Roots were used to treat swelling, and flowers as an insect repellant. Though a useful edible and medicinal plant, caution is needed. Careful not to confuse it for the poisonous water hemlock. Also the outer skin of cow parsnip can cause a skin irritation and rash when exposed to light.</p>', 7, '[{\"id\":\"1018\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240820_210409123-1018.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Cow Parsnip Patch\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"1019\",\"name\":\"PXL_20240820_195955961-1019.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Cow Parsnip Seed Head\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"1020\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230725_001048895-1020.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Cow Parsnip\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"1021\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230725_001054065-1021.jpg\",\"tag\":\"2\",\"description\":\"Cow Parsnip Leaf\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"leaves\"}]', 1),
(265, 'panicled-bulrush', 'Panicled Bulrush', 'Small-flowered Bulrush, Small-fruited Bulrush, Redstem Bulrush, Mountain Bog Bulrush, Barberpole Bulrush', 185, 'microcarpus', '', '', '', '', 4, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p>Panicled Bulrush is a perennial wetland plant, native to North America. At the top of a tall central stem, it produces an interesting globe seed head. Long green leaves have a reddish tint at their base</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Spreading through underground rhizomes, it\'s very cold tolerant and grows in a variety of temperatures. The entire plant is edible, including the leaves, stems, roots, and seeds. Used both fresh as a snack or cooked to make fours, syrups, and soups.</p>', 8, '[{\"id\":\"1037\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230627_223655210-1037.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"panicled bulrush\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"1038\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230627_223636960-1038.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"panicled bulrush\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"1039\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230627_211924210.PORTRAIT-1039.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"panicled bulrush\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"1040\",\"name\":\"PXL_20230627_223713938-1040.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"panicled bulrush\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"fruit\"},{\"id\":\"1041\",\"name\":\"PXL_20250618_182155397-1041.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"panicled bulrush\",\"caption\":\"\",\"tag_name\":\"habit\"},{\"id\":\"1053\",\"name\":\"PXL_20250621_151202701.MP-1053.jpg\",\"tag\":\"1\",\"description\":\"Panicked bulrush\",\"caption\":\"\"},{\"id\":\"1054\",\"name\":\"PXL_20250621_151145927.MP-1054.jpg\",\"tag\":\"6\",\"description\":\"Panicked bulrush\",\"caption\":\"\"}]', 2),
(266, 'echinacea', 'Echinacea', 'Purple Cone Flower', 116, '', '', '', '', '', 4, 0, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Echinacea or \"Purple Cone Flower\" is an attractive perennial flower, native to eastern and central North America. It\'s widely cultivated as an ornamental for the garden or for use as a medicinal plant, for which is has a long history.', 7, '[]', 2),
(267, 'wormwood', 'Wormwood', '', 186, 'absinthium', '', '', '', '', 4, 0, 0, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Wormwood is a tall perennial plant, traditionally used as a medicinal herb to expel parasites (hence the name wormwood). Its height, and dissected aromatic leaves give additional texture and interest the the garden.', 7, '[]', 2),
(268, 'stinging-nettle', 'Stinging Nettle', 'Common Nettle', 158, 'dioica', '', '', '', '', 4, 0, 0, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Stinging Nettle (or common Nettle) is the most widely known and used of nettles. Found around the world, it\'s originally native to Eurasia and the middle east. Despite the alarming name, stinging-nettle has a long history with so many benefits, including use as a fertilizer, medicinally, and as an edible plant. When cooked, the \"sting\" is lost and the herb is often categorized as a nutrient-rich \"super food\".', 7, '[]', 2);
